@SR4ven invalid/fuzzed payload should not cause an SSL error; however, I believe it should be treated as a test case failure. Given the code you referenced, I feel it might be worth giving the user the option to ignore SSL errors and trigger a restart of the target.

In all cases an SSL error would indicate that an EOT or socket-related error has occurred; however, the SSL API is not in a state where it has the complete encrypted data to complete the decryption. This could be caused by a connection loss before the expected encrypted data was received; or, a failed SSL-related operation (such as a session renegotiation).

In my particular case, the SSL error was thrown by ssl.recv() because my target threw a .Net stack exhaustion error. Given the particular SSL "reason" I got, it looks like the issue was the .Net SSL API ran of stack space in the process of encrypting the data that the target was attempting to send back.

