Hmm doing things like this repartition and saving to the object store as part of the logical op construction feels like an anti-pattern, since logical ops should describe the "what" that we'd like to do (i.e. basically a logical config of the operation), not perform the actual execution to do it. We also don't want to be triggering (new) Ray work until we are actually executing the dataset, if possible.

Ideally we'd capture the Spark-on-Ray dataframe and parallelism in the logical operator, and do this actual execution to convert it to a `Dataset` with a `PhysicalOperator` governed by the executor, similar to what we do when we create a `Dataset` from read tasks. Not sure how this would work best with the existing `InputDataBuffer` and the like.

